1. What is Server-Side Rendering (SSR)?

Server-Side Rendering = Django builds the HTML page on the server and sends it to the browser.

Example:

return render(request, "students/registration.html", {"form": form})


This means:

Django loads the template file.

Fills it with data (form, errors, student dataâ€¦).

Sends complete HTML to the browser.

The browser does not build the page; the server does.

This is how classic Django apps work.

âœ… 2. What Django automatically gives you (built-in security)

Django backend has many features already implemented, so you do NOT need to write them manually.

Iâ€™ll explain each simply.

ğŸ”¹ A) Cookies
âœ” Meaning

Cookies are small pieces of data stored in the user's browser.

Example cookie:

sessionid=abc123xyz


The browser sends cookies automatically with every request.

âœ” How Django uses cookies

Django stores the sessionid cookie to know who the user is.

âœ” How to check?

Open your browser â†’ Developer Tools â†’ Application â†’ Cookies.
You'll see:

sessionid
csrftoken


These are created by Django automatically.

You did not build them â€” Django built them.

ğŸ”¹ B) Sessions
âœ” Meaning

A session is a place on the server where Django stores user-related data.

Example:

request.session["student_id"] = 44


This data is stored on the server and identified by the cookie sessionid.

âœ” Why sessions are secure

Data is NOT stored in the browser.
Only a random ID is stored.
So the user cannot see or modify session data.

âœ” How to check?

You are already using it:

request.session["current_step"] = 3


Django automatically saves it in your sessionid.

ğŸ”¹ C) CSRF Protection
âœ” Meaning

CSRF = Cross-Site Request Forgery
Django automatically prevents attackers from submitting forms without your permission.

âœ” Django protection

Every POST form includes:

{% csrf_token %}


Django automatically validates this token.

âœ” How to check?

Try removing {% csrf_token %} from your form â†’
Django will show:

CSRF verification failed


This proves Django protects you.

ğŸ”¹ D) Login / Logout Decorators

Django has built-in decorators to require authentication:

from django.contrib.auth.decorators import login_required

@login_required
def dashboard(request):
    return render(request, "dashboard.html")


If the user is not logged in â†’ Django redirects them automatically.

âœ” How to check?

Visit the page without logging in â†’ you will be redirected.

ğŸ”¹ E) Permissions

Django has user roles & permissions built-in.

Examples:

Which user can add student?

Which user can edit?

Which user can delete?

You can check permissions in the admin panel â†’ Users â†’ Permissions.

Example:

from django.contrib.auth.models import Permission


Or enforce permission:

from django.contrib.auth.decorators import permission_required

@permission_required("students.change_studentregistration")
def edit_student(request):
    ...

ğŸ”¹ F) Secure Password Hashing
âœ” Meaning

Django never stores plain text passwords.

It stores hashes like:

pbkdf2_sha256$260000$fjdkir43...$asd9sdASD92...


These cannot be reversed.

âœ” How to check?

In your DB, look at:

auth_user


Password column is hashed, not readable.

âœ” You donâ€™t need to implement hashing

Django does it automatically when you create a user:

user.set_password("mypassword")

ğŸ”¹ G) User Authentication System

This includes:

Login

Logout

Password hashing

Session management

Permissions

Groups

Password reset

Admin interface authentication

Django gives all this when you write:

INSTALLED_APPS = [
    "django.contrib.auth",
    "django.contrib.sessions",
]

ğŸŸ¦ 3. Why does this mean you donâ€™t need JWT?

Because Django templates communicate directly with the server; the server handles:

âœ” Login
âœ” Who the user is
âœ” Permissions
âœ” Sessions
âœ” Cookies
âœ” Authorization
âœ” CSRF

JWT is used only when:

You have React

You have mobile apps

You have external clients

You are building an API system

For server-rendered Django websites â†’ Djangoâ€™s built-in session auth is more secure and easier.

ğŸŸ¢ 4. If Django already has these features, how do you â€œactivateâ€ them?

You already activated them.
Django auto-activates them when you include the following in settings.py:

INSTALLED_APPS = [
    "django.contrib.auth",
    "django.contrib.contenttypes",
    "django.contrib.sessions",
    "django.contrib.messages",
]


and in middleware:

MIDDLEWARE = [
    "django.contrib.sessions.middleware.SessionMiddleware",
    "django.middleware.csrf.CsrfViewMiddleware",
    "django.contrib.auth.middleware.AuthenticationMiddleware",
]


Nothing more is needed.

